('chunk_aac09f6cbb963d613a','file_04bb580a3d99034261','history.md','Chapter 3.2 — Early Explorers','**Factual grounding.** Key figures who opened new routes and knowledge:
- **Marco Polo (1254–1324):** Venetian merchant-traveller whose account of his journey to **Kublai Khan''s China** along the Silk Route (published c. 1300) fed European fascination with Asia''s wealth. (He predates the sea-voyage Age of Exploration but inspired it.)
- **Zheng He (1371–1433):** Chinese Ming-dynasty admiral who led **seven massive treasure-fleet voyages (1405–1433)** across the Indian Ocean to Southeast Asia, India, Arabia and East Africa — decades before the Portuguese, with far larger ships.
- **Bartolomeu Dias (c. 1450–1500):** Portuguese explorer who in **1488** became the first European to round the southern tip of Africa (the **Cape of Good Hope**), proving a sea route toward the Indian Ocean was possible.
- **Vasco da Gama (c. 1460s–1524):** Portuguese explorer who **reached Calicut (Kozhikode), India, by sea in 1498**, opening the direct ocean route from Europe to India around Africa.

**Significance.** These voyages connected previously separate worlds, launched European maritime empires and the global spice/trade economy, and showed that non-European powers (Ming China) were world-leading navigators.

**Perspective/interpretation note.** Zheng He''s voyages were largely diplomatic/tributary, not colonising; the Portuguese voyages were about seizing trade and territory. Comparing them challenges a Europe-only view of exploration.

**Misconception:** *"Europeans were the first and only advanced ocean explorers."*
- *Why believed:* Western textbooks foreground Columbus and da Gama.
- *Why wrong:* **Zheng He''s Chinese fleets (from 1405)** sailed vast distances in enormous ships decades before da Gama''s 1498 voyage; Arab, Indian and Polynesian navigators had long crossed oceans.
- *Corrective:* Ocean exploration was a global phenomenon; Europeans were not first, only later dominant.','{"1254":1,"1300":1,"1324":1,"1371":1,"1405":2,"1433":2,"1450":1,"1488":1,"1498":2,"1500":1,"1524":1,"chapter":1,"early":1,"explorers":2,"factual":1,"grounding":1,"key":1,"figures":1,"who":4,"opened":1,"new":1,"routes":1,"and":8,"knowledge":1,"marco":1,"polo":1,"venetian":1,"merchant":1,"traveller":1,"whose":1,"account":1,"his":1,"journey":1,"kublai":1,"khan":1,"china":2,"along":1,"the":12,"silk":1,"route":3,"published":1,"fed":1,"european":4,"fascination":1,"with":2,"asia":2,"wealth":1,"predates":1,"sea":3,"voyage":2,"age":1,"exploration":3,"but":1,"inspired":1,"zheng":3,"chinese":2,"ming":2,"dynasty":1,"admiral":1,"led":1,"seven":1,"massive":1,"treasure":1,"fleet":1,"voyages":4,"across":1,"indian":3,"ocean":5,"southeast":1,"india":3,"arabia":1,"east":1,"africa":3,"decades":2,"before":2,"portuguese":4,"far":1,"larger":1,"ships":2,"bartolomeu":1,"dias":1,"explorer":2,"became":1,"first":3,"round":1,"southern":1,"tip":1,"cape":1,"good":1,"hope":1,"proving":1,"toward":1,"was":2,"possible":1,"vasco":1,"gama":3,"1460s":1,"reached":1,"calicut":1,"kozhikode":1,"opening":1,"direct":1,"from":2,"europe":2,"around":1,"significance":1,"these":1,"connected":1,"previously":1,"separate":1,"worlds":1,"launched":1,"maritime":1,"empires":1,"global":2,"spice":1,"trade":2,"economy":1,"showed":1,"that":1,"non":1,"powers":1,"were":5,"world":1,"leading":1,"navigators":2,"perspective":1,"interpretation":1,"note":1,"largely":1,"diplomatic":1,"tributary":1,"not":2,"colonising":1,"about":1,"seizing":1,"territory":1,"comparing":1,"them":1,"challenges":1,"only":3,"view":1,"misconception":1,"europeans":2,"advanced":1,"why":2,"believed":1,"western":1,"textbooks":1,"foreground":1,"columbus":1,"wrong":1,"fleets":1,"sailed":1,"vast":1,"distances":1,"enormous":1,"arab":1,"polynesian":1,"had":1,"long":1,"crossed":1,"oceans":1,"corrective":1,"phenomenon":1,"later":1,"dominant":1}'::jsonb),
